An automatic peritoneal dialysis system for performing continuous cyclic peritoneal dialysis of the type which includes a fluid circuit for delivering sterile peritoneal dialysate to the peritoneal cavity of a patient during fill cycles and removing spent dialysate during drain cycles; and a system controller for controlling the flow of dialysate during said fill and drain cycles, wherein said system comprises:
a supply of unsterilized dialysate (B) available on demand;
an inflow line segment included in said fluid circuit for delivering dialysate from said supply to the patient during said fill cycles;
an outflow line segment included in said fluid circuit for connection to the patient's peritoneal cavity to drain spent dialysate from the peritoneal cavity during said drain cycles; characterized by
an in-line sterilization filter assembly (E, F) disposed in said inflow line segment for real time sterilization of said unsterilized dialysate during flow of said dialysate in said inflow line segment prior to patient delivery;
said sterilization filter assembly including an inlet port (108) connected in said inflow line segment for receiving unsterilized dialysate, a sterilization filter medium (202) through which said dialysate passes for producing sterilized dialysate, and an outlet port (110) connected in said inflow line segment (L2) through which sterilized dialysate flows for delivery to the patient during the peritoneal dialysis;
a filter test component (D) operatively associated with said sterilization filter assembly for conducting a real time integrity test on said filter assembly to test for a filter failure condition which would allow contaminants into said dialysate prior to patient delivery; and
a test sensor (56, 58) in communication with said testing component for detecting said failure condition;
whereby said fill and drain cycles may be continuously repeated by the system controller as needed to complete peritoneal dialysis with a generally constant supply of sterilized peritoneal dialysate available on demand.

The system of claim 1 induding:
an inflow sensor (30, 32, 34) in communication with said inflow line for measuring an inflow volume of said dialysate through said inflow line and generating an inflow signal;
an outflow sensor (44, 46, 48) in communication with said outflow line for measuring an outflow volume of said dialysate through said outflow line and generating an outflow signal;
said system controller (16) for controlling said inflow and outflow delivery in response to said inflow and outflow signals during said fill and drain cycles; and
a proportioning sensor (30, 32, 34) (44, 46, 48) responsive to said inflow and outflow volumes for determining a volume of body waste fluid removed from the patient's peritoneal cavity during said fill and drain cycles; and said control system (16, 38) controlling said proportioning sensor in response to said volume of fluid and controlling said fill and drain cycles until a desired amount of waste is removed from the patient.

An in-line, real time dialysis fluid sterilization process to produce a sterilized dialysate for continuous cyclic peritoneal dialysis comprising:
preparing an unsterilized osmotic dialysate effective for dialysis;
passing said dialysate through at least one in-line sterilization filter assembly connected in an inflow line in real time during the process and prior to delivery to the patient;
testing said sterilization filter assembly in real time during the process for a filter failure condition prior to delivering said dialysate to the peritoneal cavity of said patient and
accumulating the dialysate after passing the dialysate through said sterilization filter assembly, testing the integrity of said sterilization filter assembly while the dialysate is accumulated and discarding the retained dialysate if the integrity test is failed.

